Chapter One — Primo

Kamile finished the clay man’s face on the third morning.  He worked slowly with his smallest tools, which he kept wrapped in oilcloth.  He gave him a broad nose, a low brow and a mouth that settled into a natural, almost‑smile—one that made strangers feel they were already known.  He made the ears stick out slightly; perfection unnerved him, and he’d never trusted a man with perfect ears.

When he was finished, he sat back and looked.  You, he thought.  Let’s see what you do with it.

He did not name him yet.  He never named them until they had been awake long enough to deserve it.  The soul was present, but a man is completed in his first hours of moving through a world that resists him.  Kamile had learned to wait.

On the third morning, the clay man—who would later be called Primo—sat up like someone who has slept longer than intended.  He examined his hands, turning them over, pressing fingertip to fingertip and noting the resistance with satisfaction—or at least without alarm.  Then he looked at Kamile with the eyes Kamile had given him—dark, deep‑set and patient.  He said nothing because he had no language yet, only a dawning awareness of being.  For a first morning, that is enough.

Over the following weeks, Kamile taught him Greek.  Primo learned steadily, without drama, absorbing what he was given and quietly asking for more.  He had a gift for names.  He wanted to know what everything was called: tools, hills, birds that came to the high window.  He pointed and waited.  Hawk, Kamile would say.  Primo would repeat it, nodding as though filing it away.

He was a good man.  Kamile had felt it in the making—how evenly the soul had settled, without resistance, like oil finding its level.  Some souls fought even as they entered, though “fought” was not quite right—hesitated.  Primo accepted what he was given and became completely himself.

It was Primo who chose the sea.  Kamile never directed his creations toward particular lives.  He gave them language, a sense of the world and practical knowledge enough to find their footing.  Then he let them pursue whatever drew them.  He had learned that the pull came from the soul—his soul, divided and specific to each man, each fragment carrying a piece of his own inclination.  Kamile had always loved water, so it did not surprise him when, on his fourteenth day, Primo walked down to the coast, stood at its edge for a long time and returned with his hands at his sides and his face doing something no language named.

“I want to fish,” he said.

“Then fish,” Kamile replied.

Kamile found him a place among the fishermen of a small harbour three hours’ walk away: a cove with a dozen boats and a community organised around the sea, as such places always are—practical, superstitious and suspicious of anyone from inland.  Primo was from inland.

It took him two weeks to be accepted.  He succeeded as one must: by being useful before being liked.  He learned the nets and the tides.  He learned which older fishermen wanted conversation before dawn and which wanted silence, and he supplied whichever was needed without appearing to notice.  He had that almost‑smile, and strangers felt known by it.  Within a month, every man in the harbour felt Primo had been there longer than he had.

He was happy.  Kamile visited twice that first season, watching from the hillside and taking care with his feelings.  The joy planted in him remained, but he knew how easily it could resemble pride.  Pride was not the point.  The work was simple and painful: make a man who is happy.  That was all it had ever been.

At first, neither of them noticed the damage.  Primo saw it before Kamile did but said nothing because he did not know what he saw.  He only noticed that the skin of his forearms, after a day at sea, looked different—smoother, less defined, like a riverbank after a season of water.

By the second year, it was clear to anyone who looked, though the fishermen didn’t.  They saw each other as colleagues, competitors or friends—not through eyes attuned to deterioration.  But Kamile noticed the third time he visited.  Sitting with Primo on the harbour wall in afternoon light, he looked at his hands and felt something drop through him.  The fingers worked, but the edges had softened.  The knuckles he had shaped with care were rounding off, the way stone smooths under a fountain.

“Does it hurt?” Kamile asked.

Primo considered seriously.  “No.  Should it?”

“I don’t know,” Kamile said, truthfully.

They sat awhile.

“I know what I am,” Primo said—not as accusation but as statement.  He had always learned by observation and patience.  “You made me.”

“Yes.”

“I’m made of earth, and the sea is taking me back.”

Kamile said nothing.

“That seems,” Primo said, pausing to watch the late light turn the water gold, the boats knocking gently together, “like something the gods would arrange.”

“Yes,” Kamile said.  “It does.”

Primo nodded, interested rather than distressed.  He had always wanted to know what things were called.  He filed this away and looked at the sea.

He fished for another year.  By then his face had lost its fine detail—the angle of the nose, the slight asymmetry of the ears.  He was becoming simpler: a shape that suggested “man” without insisting on it.  Yet he still knew the nets, the tides and which fishermen needed silence before dawn.  He still provided it.

One morning he went out alone to deeper water where the serious fish were.  The others watched him go without concern.  There was nothing yet to fear.  When he hadn’t returned by noon, they searched and found his boat drifting.  The nets were neatly stowed; the oars were shipped.  There were no signs of struggle or anything out of place—just the boat and the water, untroubled, going down into darkness, taking back what it had been given.

Kamile heard two days later.  He walked to the cove, stood where he had sat with Primo and thought about fingers and softened edges.

He thought: waterproof.

He returned to the workshop, set his hands in the clay and began again.

