Chapter Two — Yiorgos

Kamile approached his next creation differently.  He thought about Primo not with grief alone but with the attention of a craftsman reviewing his work for error.  Sitting at the long table, he turned the problem over in his mind as he turned the clay.

The answer was simple, and he disliked it for its simplicity.  He had made Primo of earth and sent him to live on water without considering what water does to earth over time.  He had not thought like a potter.  He had thought like a father, which was the mistake.  Fathers do not think about material.  They think about the child.

He would not repeat that.

For Yiorgos he spent three days choosing clay, climbing further up the hillside than usual to a deposit above the treeline, where centuries of pressure made it dense and serious.  He kneaded it longer than necessary, past readiness, until it was tighter and less willing to yield.  He mixed in a small amount of fired clay, ground fine: strength inside softness—a skeleton of what had survived fire.

He was pleased with the material.

He waterproofed less thoroughly than he would later, applying a fine surface treatment he had devised over winter—a sealing that left the appearance unchanged but closed the pores against water and weather.  Primo had been open to everything; Yiorgos would be shielded from the worst.

Kamile built him broad and unhurried.  Not a soldier’s body—this man was not for war.  A farmer’s body built for long, repetitive work: shoulders to carry, a back that could bend all day and straighten again, hands with grip.  As always, he did the face last.  He gave Yiorgos a wide, patient face with creases around the eyes, as though he spent his life looking far ahead, and a mouth that didn’t smile easily but meant it when it did.

He pressed his thumb into the chest and felt a piece of himself leave.

Yiorgos opened his eyes, looked at the ceiling and breathed.  He accepted life immediately.  He took to the land as Primo had taken to the sea—not by decision but by recognition.

Kamile found him a farm two days’ walk east: a modest holding in a valley with a house, a barn, an olive grove, two fields and a horse named by no one in particular—Kephos, a large bay with a calm eye that had been left with a neighbour and seemed pleased to have someone permanent again.  Yiorgos surveyed the property in silence.

“The olives need attention,” he said at last.

“Yes,” Kamile replied.

“I’ll start there.”

He did.  He pruned the olives hard and they rewarded him the next season.  He turned the fields, learned their drainage and planted accordingly.  He repaired the stone walls with pleasure rather than obligation.  He named the horse Kephos because it sounded right and treated him with the quiet patience of someone who understands that animals respond to consistency, not force.

Kamile visited in the second season and found him content.  Not happy like Primo—whose joy had been immediate and bright—but quietly satisfied, the kind that announces itself only in its absence.  He fed Kamile, showed him the grove and discussed the soil as one still learning it.  He had good neighbours and a steady rhythm.

“You seem well,” Kamile said.

“I am well,” Yiorgos answered, as if confirming a measurement.

Kamile walked home and allowed himself to feel joy fully, alone on the road with hills glowing around him.  It was his joy.  Entirely his.

Then came the fire.

No one knew the cause.  On dry farms, fires happen: a lamp, a spark, built‑up heat.  Yiorgos woke to smoke and found the stable already burning, orange light enormous in the dark, Kephos’s frantic sounds loud and continuous.  Neighbours formed a bucket line and attacked the blaze with the urgency of people accustomed to how fast fire moves and how much it takes.

Yiorgos looked at the stable, at the bucket line, and made a calculation.  He didn’t hesitate.  He went in through a side door that had not yet caught, straight into Kephos’s stall, moving low and fast, speaking to the horse in his low, constant murmur—I’m here, nothing will hurt you.  The smoke was thick and the heat immense, a weight with intent.

He reached Kephos.  The horse was beyond reassurance—white‑eyed, crashing against walls.  Yiorgos grabbed his halter and held on.

What the fire was doing to him he could not feel; he had no nerves.  His clay, though mixed and sealed, was softening from the moment he entered.  The horse weighed more than two men and pulled with everything he had.  Yiorgos held on.  He held on because he was made from a soul that always held on.

The separation was quiet, like cutting wet clay with a wire.  His upper half still held the halter for a moment longer than it should have.  Then he lay on the stable floor.  Kephos burst through the door into the night.  The fire consumed everything.

When the neighbours found him later, they did not understand what they saw.  They stood in the ruins in the grey morning and tried to explain it to each other in quiet voices.  They were confused more than frightened.  One older man crouched and rubbed the clay between his fingers thoughtfully.  They buried what remained under the olive grove because it felt right.  The trees thrived there for many years, and people remarked on it without knowing why it felt significant.

They found Kephos two fields over, unhurt, grazing calmly.

Kamile heard and walked east.  He stood among the olives and thought about what heat did before the horse did.  He thought about structure and what holds under pressure.  He thought: strength—real strength, not density; something that doesn’t soften.  He thought about a soldier—about a man who could bear the weight of the world and not break.

He walked back to the workshop and the waiting clay.

