Chapter Three — Atlas

Kamile built Atlas like an argument.  Every decision answered Yiorgos’s death: the stable floor, the clean separation, the old man rubbing clay between his fingers.  Kamile had lain awake with that image too many nights.

He dug deeper into the upland deposit, below the layer he had used for Yiorgos, to where clay was almost stone.  It came out dark and resistant.  He worked it for days; his hands and wrists ached.  Good, he thought.  If it fights me, it will fight everything.

He fired sections in his kiln, then ground the fired clay and mixed it back into the raw material.  He repeated this three times.  The result was unlike any clay he had used—a material that pushed back instead of yielding.

He built Atlas large, at the edge of what men are—not grotesque, but a man who made doorframes seem like suggestions.  The chest was deep, the shoulders broad, the neck thick enough to support a head capable of decisions under weight.  He built the back carefully, layer by layer, like a wall that must last, always placing something behind wherever the force would pass through.  He built strong legs meant to carry the weight of a man in full bronze marching on bad terrain for as long as necessary.  Running never occurred to him; he was thinking about standing and holding.

He gave Atlas a broad, serious face—heavy brows, a jaw suggesting conclusions rather than questions, eyes set wide and level.  He pressed his thumb to the chest.  The piece of himself that left was larger than usual.  He had become practised at this loss, but practice brings no immunity.  Each time was new.

Atlas opened his eyes, looked at the ceiling and breathed.  The breathing was slower, deeper—bellows rather than lungs.  He sat up easily and looked at his hands, then at Kamile with a face already waiting for information.

“You’ll want to stand,” Kamile said.

Atlas stood.  He filled the room differently than the others—not aggressively but inevitably.  The room reorganised itself around him.  The ceiling seemed lower, the walls nearer.  He existed in a way that rearranged space.

“Good,” Kamile said, and meant it.

He did not send Atlas to war, nor did Atlas seek violence.  Instead, he became a guardian—a protector of smaller things.  He settled in a mountain community three days north, a place of goatherds and farmers living on a pass connecting two valleys.  Weather came fast, terrain was unforgiving, and people often needed strength more than strategy.

Atlas helped with everything.  He steadied collapsing roofs, freed trapped animals and moved heavy objects.  Emergencies that arrived suddenly and required someone to stand in a bad place and hold on found him ready.  He was good at this as naturally as Primo had been with the sea and Yiorgos with the land.

The settlement accepted him as mountain people accept useful things: without excessive sentiment but with deep reliability.  He belonged to them.  They sent for him when matters were serious.

He rarely talked.  Language had been given to him, but he used it sparingly, understanding that most situations require action before words.  When he spoke, people listened because his words always had weight.

Kamile visited his guardian in the first winter.  They sat by the fire in the communal hall and said little.  The joy moved through Kamile.  “Are you content?” he asked.

Atlas considered.  “I am where I should be.”

Kamile thought that might be the best answer he had ever received.

He was with Atlas on the mountain when the pass gave way.

He had come for a second visit, following the high path with his satchel over one shoulder—tools, oilcloth, and a quantity of dark clay he now carried habitually.  The sky had looked wrong since morning—a grey mountains produce when they are about to act.  Kamile noted it but continued; he had visited his creations long enough to develop the stubbornness of old men about weather.

They were on a narrow traverse where the path ran along the cliff face, the valley far below.  The mountain moved—not all at once.  First a deep, structural sound that arrived in the chest before the ears.  Then a crack above, sharp and definite.  Then small rocks, scattering.  Then the rest.

Kamile looked up and felt cold move through him.  He looked at Atlas.  Atlas was already examining the bottleneck ahead, where the path narrowed to a single man’s width—the throat where the rockslide would funnel.  He looked at Kamile’s satchel, the tools and clay pressing against the fabric.  His eyes, made to measure distance accurately, assessed and concluded.

Kamile opened his mouth.  “Atlas—”

Atlas placed his hand on Kamile’s chest and pushed him toward the narrow section—not roughly, simply, with finality, like closing a door.

“Go,” he said.

“Atlas—”

“Go.”

He turned around.  He walked to where the path widened slightly, where a man his size could stand across it and become a wall.  He planted his feet.  The rocks came down.  He held.

Kamile ran.

He ran through the bottleneck with rocks hammering above, dust filling the air, the sound immense.  He did not look back because he couldn’t.  If he looked, he would stop, and if he stopped, Atlas’s choice would be wasted.  He emerged on the other side and ran until he could run no further.

Dust settled.  The narrow section was gone, replaced by a raw heap of stone sealing the pass.  Atlas was nowhere.  Only the mountain remained, rearranged.

Kamile knelt on the path.  The valley below was distant; someone called out, their voice small.  He thought about the hand on his chest, the satchel, the calculation in Atlas’s eyes.  Atlas died so the next one could live, he thought.  He knew that.  He saw what I carried and understood.

He placed his hand on the satchel and felt the tools and clay.  Then he stood and walked toward the valley, thinking about legs—about speed and lightness and the capacity to cover ground quickly.  He thought: run.

Behind him, the mountain was quiet and entirely finished with the matter.

