Chapter Four — Androcles

Androcles returned from war the way men do who have seen too much of what they went for.  He was not broken or hollowed, but he was changed—quietly and permanently.  He walked back into the valley one autumn morning with his pack on his back, his sword at his hip and the look of someone finished with something and unsure what came next.

He had heard of Kamile as unusual stories are told—indirectly, through the silence that surrounds them: the sculptor on the hill, the men he makes, how they live and die, and how he keeps making them.  Most people who heard felt fear and unease and wanted to talk about something else.  Androcles felt something different.

Three days after his return, he climbed the hill and knocked on the workshop door.  In the early light he said, “I want to learn how to make something live.”

Kamile studied him: the soldier’s bearing, the soldier’s eyes and something underneath moving away from what he’d been.  “Why?”

“Because I’ve spent four years learning how to end things,” Androcles said.  “And I’m done with that.”

Kamile stood back.  “Come in, then.”

Androcles was a good student in the way those who come to learning by choice and late can be.  He had seriousness the young seldom manage and the patience of someone who knows impatience kills.  His hands were skilled and needed only to be retrained.

At first, he was not gentle.  His hands knew force and applied it.  The clay resisted, and he applied more.  Kamile watched for three days before speaking.

“You’re trying to win,” Kamile said.

Androcles looked up.

“The clay isn’t an opponent,” Kamile said.  “You’re not trying to defeat it.  You’re trying to discover what it wants to be.”

“That’s not how I was taught,” Androcles said.

“No,” Kamile said.  “I imagine not.”

It took almost a year to unlearn force, but he did.  By winter’s end, he could work clay for hours with the attentive quality Kamile recognised and valued.  They worked side by side most mornings, sometimes talking, sometimes not.  Their silence was the good kind—two people doing the same thing and both knowing it.

In the afternoons Kamile taught him theory.  Not the soul—no one can teach that—but everything around it: selecting clay, preparation, workable proportions, surface treatments and firing techniques.  It was the hard knowledge Kamile had paid for with four lives.  For the first time, he passed it on.

“Why do you keep going?” Androcles asked one evening in the second year.  They were outside, the valley darkening and the first stars appearing.  It was the kind of question for that kind of evening.

Kamile thought.  “Because I love it.  Because when they breathe—for the first time—I feel something I can’t feel any other way.”

“Even knowing what happens after?”

“Yes.”

Androcles was quiet.  “That’s either very wise or very foolish.”

“I’ve never been sure which,” Kamile said.

Androcles almost smiled—Kamile recognised the expression from Primo and realised he had given away a part of himself without knowing.  “I think doing what you love, knowing the cost, is the only honest way to live,” Androcles said.

Kamile looked at the stars and said nothing, feeling joy move through him like weather.

By the third year Androcles could build a man.  He could not bring him to life—only Kamile could give the soul—but he could shape one from raw material with a confidence no longer that of a student.  His hands had completed their retraining.  One day, he presented a clay man.  Kamile walked around it, looking from every angle.

“Well?” Androcles asked.

“The left shoulder,” Kamile said.  Androcles nodded, adjusted.  “Better,” Kamile said.  “The face?”

“The face is good,” Kamile answered after studying it.  “Very good.”  Androcles had given the man a mouth that rested in an almost‑smile.  Kamile noticed and did not mention it.

In the fourth year, Androcles began asking about the soul.  Carefully, with the patience he had learned from clay, he asked what it felt like, what left and what remained, whether the piece that went into the clay returned when a clay man died.

“It doesn’t return,” Kamile said.  “I keep giving it.”

“How much do you have left?”

“Enough for one,” Kamile said.  “Perhaps.”

Androcles took this in as he had taken in difficult information in the field—steadily.  “Then we have to make sure the next one is right,” he said.

“Yes,” Kamile said.

“Tell me everything you haven’t told me.”

So Kamile told him.  Primo and the sea; Yiorgos, the fire and the horse; Atlas, the mountain and the hand on his chest; the satchel, the tools and the calculation.  Androcles listened with his hands still and his eyes level.  When Kamile finished, he was quiet.

“Atlas died so you could be here,” Androcles said.

“Yes.”

“So you could make the next one.”

“Yes.”

“And I’m meant to carry it on,” Androcles said—not a question, just naming the fact.

“That was what I hoped,” Kamile said.

Androcles nodded slowly, looking at his hands—the hands that had unlearned force, the hands that could build a man with a good face.  “Then I’d better learn the rest,” he said.

It was an ordinary late‑summer afternoon: hot, bright, the smell of dry grass and insects in the valley.  Androcles went to the upland deposit for clay—a familiar path he could have walked blindfolded.  He carried two empty buckets, moving easily.

Kamile was in the workshop working on a new surface treatment.  He was absorbed when it happened.  The gods were fighting far above—actually fighting, not through signs or weather.  Bolts of divine violence shed off like sparks from a hammer.  One stray bolt fell through the clear sky and struck the path where Androcles walked with his buckets and hands that knew how to find what clay wanted to be.

Kamile felt it through the workshop floor before he heard it.  He was outside before the sound ended.

The path above was scorched along a single, decisive line.  Two buckets lay as they had been—one upright, one on its side.  The air smelled of something completely reduced from one thing to nothing.  There was no Androcles, no trace.  The afternoon continued indifferent: insects hummed, light persisted.

Kamile stood on the path a long time.  He did not look at the sky.  The gods were gone, their argument continuing elsewhere, already done with this valley.  They had not noticed.  They had not even noticed.

He crouched and touched the scorched earth.  Still warm.  He thought of four years of mornings, of hands learning to loosen, of an almost‑smile on a face Androcles had made without knowing its origin.  Enough for one, he had said.  Perhaps.

He stayed until the earth cooled and the evening came.  Then he picked up the buckets—leaving them felt wrong—and carried them back to the workshop.  He sat at the long table with the last of his clay and his tools.  He thought about Atlas’s hand and Androcles’s words.  He thought about a name he had not yet used: Loretto, victory.

