Chapter Five — Loretto

The workshop was dark except for a single lamp.  Kamile hadn’t lit it intentionally; his hand had moved on its own, the body keeping busy while the mind went where the body could not follow.  The lamp cast a small circle of yellow light over the clay and the tools wrapped in oilcloth.  The final piece of his soul sat in his chest like a stone and a seed.

He had been sitting a long time.  Outside, the valley was dark, stars scattered overhead and a night bird called, indifferent yet somehow comforting.  The world was ready to continue without him.  The clay waited, patient and opinionless.

He thought about the gods.  He thought about confronting them in a high place above the weather.  He imagined waiting until they noticed him, reminding them they had made him for this, that they had given him not just compulsion but joy—the love that would keep him going and fund their experiment with his happiness.  He imagined accusing them of making his love serve their purpose.  He imagined them explaining that love was his alone, that purpose inevitably follows what is genuine.  He imagined asking about Primo, Yiorgos and Atlas; he imagined their reverence for Atlas’s choice.  He imagined asking about Androcles.  There would be silence—Androcles was not design or purpose, merely a stray bolt from a divine argument.  Their silence would be honest.  He imagined asking why they allow such bolts.  “We don’t govern every detail,” they would say.  He imagined asking what they were for.  “The same thing you are for,” they would answer.  “We make things.”

But these were only thoughts—journeys that return with no answers, only a clearer shape of the question.  He was still at the table with clay and the last piece of himself.  The decision would not arrive as certainty but as choice.  Choices are harder and more meaningful.

He thought about Primo: the broad nose, the almost‑smile, the way he accepted his nature and looked at the sea.  He thought about Yiorgos: his silence in the olive grove, the soil he was still learning, the grove that thrived where he lay.  He thought about the place in himself around Atlas that still ached and could not be approached directly.  He thought about Androcles: wanting to create life after ending lives, unlearning force, saying that to do what you love while knowing the cost is the only honest way to live.  He thought about that almost‑smile resurfacing unexpectedly.  He thought about Atlas’s hand on his chest.  He thought about Androcles’s promise to learn the rest, cut short by a bolt the gods did not even aim.

He thought about what it would mean to keep the last piece of his soul for himself—to live mornings and evenings without the cost of making.  He tried to imagine life without making and found it an unknown landscape his mind couldn’t map.  Perhaps that inability came from the love the gods had planted, disguising itself as his own imagination’s limit.  Perhaps not.  He didn’t know.

He placed his hand on the clay.  The cool, dense upland clay he had prepared over weeks without deciding—a reflex—waited with its usual patience.  He thought of Loretto, the name he had never used.  Victory.  But victory for whom?  If he made Loretto and Loretto lived and carried the craft onward, would that be his triumph or the gods’?  Was there a difference?  The gods might say the love came from him and was always his, but his work had served their purpose.  Did that matter?  He didn’t know.

He thought about Atlas.  Someone died so he could sit at this table.  Atlas turned so he could be here with clay and tools and the last of himself.  That fact required no answer; it simply sat with him.  He thought about all the men he had not made yet.  He thought about the joy he felt when the chest rose and fell for the first time.  That joy was his, entirely his, whatever the gods intended.

He sat with the weight of his choice.  Outside, the night bird fell silent.  Dawn lightened the edge of the hills.  The earth waited, patient, ready, without opinion.  The gods were elsewhere, already arguing about something new.  The lamp flickered.

Kamile sat.  Only he could decide.  It had always been his choice.

